# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abortion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] The **1917 *Code of Canon Law*** (abbreviated **1917 CIC**, from its Latin title ***Codex Iuris Canonici***), also referred to as the **Pio-Benedictine Code**, is the first official comprehensive codification of Latin canon law.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] Ordered by Pope Pius X in 1904 and carried out by the Commission for the Codification of Canon Law, led by Pietro Cardinal Gasparri, the work to produce the code was completed and promulgated under Pope Benedict XV on 27 May 1917, coming into effect on 19 May 1918.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] The 1917 *Code of Canon Law* has been described as "the greatest revolution in canon law since the time of Gratian" (1150s AD).
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] The 1917 *Code of Canon Law* was composed of laws called canons, of which there were 2,414.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] It remained in force until the 1983 *Code of Canon Law* took legal effect and abrogated it on 27 November 1983.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] Papal attempts at codification of the scattered mass of canon law spanned the eight centuries since Gratian produced his *Decretum* c.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] The five books of the *Decretales Gregorii IX* and the *Liber Sextus* of Boniface VIII were later published.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] Since the close of the *Corpus Juris*, numerous new laws and decrees had been issued by popes, councils, and Roman Congregations.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] Moreover, not a few ordinances, whether included in the "Corpus Juris" or of more recent date, appeared to be contradictory; some had been formally abrogated, others had become obsolete by long disuse; others, again, had ceased to be useful or applicable in the present condition of society.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] Great confusion was thus engendered and correct knowledge of the law rendered very difficult even for those who had to enforce it.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] In addition to the canon law experts brought to Rome to serve on the codification commission, all the Latin Church's bishops and superiors general of religious orders were periodically consulted via letter.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] Every Latin bishop had the right to permanently keep a representative in Rome to give him voice at the meetings of the codification commission.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] By the winter of 1912, the "whole span of the code" had been completed, so that a provisional text was printed.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] Under the aegis of Cardinal Pietro Gasparri, with the help of Eugenio Pacelli (who later became Pope Pius XII), the Commission for the Codification of Canon Law completed its work under Benedict XV, who promulgated the *Code* which became effective in 1918.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] The work having been begun by Pius X and being promulgated by Benedict XV, it is sometimes called the "Pio-Benedictine Code".
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] The code was promulgated on 27 May 1917, Pentecost Sunday, as the *Code of Canon Law* (Latin: *Codex Iuris Canonici*) by Pope Benedict XV's apostolic constitution *Providentissima Mater Ecclesia*.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] Benedict XV set 19 May 1918 as the date on which it came into force.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] On 15 September 1917, by the *motu proprio* *Cum Iuris Canonici*, Pope Benedict XV made provision for a Pontifical Commission charged with interpreting the code and making any necessary modifications as later legislation was issued.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] New laws would be appended to existing canons in new paragraphs or inserted between canons, repeating the number of the previous canon and adding *bis*, *ter*, etc.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] "canon 1567*bis*" in the style of the civil law) so as not to subvert the ordering of the code, or the existing text of a canon would be completely supplanted.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] The numbering of the canons was not to be altered.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] For the most part, it applied only to the Latin Church except when "it treats of things that, by their nature, apply to the Oriental".
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] The Latin text of the 1917 *Code* remained unchanged for the first 30 years of its enactment, when Pope Pius XII issued a *motu proprio* of 1 August 1948 that amended canon 1099 of the code, a revision that took effect on 1 January 1949.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] The 1917 *Code* was in force until canon 6 §1 1° of the 1983 *Code of Canon Law* took legal effect—thereby abrogating it—on 27 November 1983.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] The congregations were instead to issue Instructions on the canons of the code, and to make it clear that they were elucidating particular canons of the code.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] This was done so as not to make the code obsolete soon after it was promulgated.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] The 1917 *Code* was very rarely amended, and then only slightly.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] The organization of the 1917 *Code* followed the divisions (*Personae*, *Res*, *Actiones*) of the ancient Roman jurists Gaius and Justinian.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] The code did not follow the classical canonical divisions (*Iudex*, *Iudicium*, *Clerus*, *Sponsalia*, *Crimen*).
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] During the 65 years of its enforcement, a complete translation of the 1917 *Code* from its original Latin was never published.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] Translations were forbidden, partly to ensure that interpretive disputes among scholars and canonists concerning such a new type of code would be resolved in Latin itself and not in one of the many languages used in scholarship.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] More English-language research material exists relating to the 1917 Code than in any other language except Latin.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] The book *De rebus* ('On things') was subject to much criticism due to its inclusion of supernatural subjects such as sacraments and divine worship under the category "things" and due to its amalgamation of disparate subject matter.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] It was argued by some that this was a legalistic reduction of sacramental mystery.
[src:abortion/1917-code-of-canon-law] René Metz defended the codifiers' decision on the layout and scope of *De rebus* as being the "least bad solution" to structural problems which the codifiers themselves fully understood.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] The general risks of ultrasound also apply to 3D ultrasound.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] Essentially, ultrasound is considered safe.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] While other imaging modalities use radioactive dye or ionizing radiation, for example, ultrasound transducers send pulses of high frequency sound into the body and then listen for the echo.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] In summary, the primary risks associated with ultrasound would be the potential heating of tissue or cavitation.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] The mechanisms by which tissue heating and cavitation are measured are through the standards called thermal index (TI) and mechanical index (MI).
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] Even though the FDA outlines very safe values for maximum TI and MI, it is still recommended to avoid unnecessary ultrasound imaging.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] 3D ultrasound is useful, among other things, for facilitating the characterization of some congenital defects, such as skeletal anomalies and heart issues.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] With real-time 3D ultrasound, the fetal heart rate can be examined in real-time.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] Applications of three-dimensional ultrasound in cardiac treatment have achieved outstanding progress in scanning and treating heart issues.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] When 3D ultrasound is used to visualize the cardiac state of an individual, it is called 3D echocardiography.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] With the integration of other technologies, it is possible to obtain quantitative measurements such as chamber volume during the cardiac cycle.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] It also provides other useful information, for example, tracking the blood flow, or the speed of contractions and expansions.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] With 3D echocardiography, physicians can detect artery diseases with relative ease, and can finely examine various cardiac defects.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] 3D echocardiography can achieve real-time imaging of the cardiac structure.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] Traditionally, with 2D ultrasound, the specific position of organs and tissues, which is useful in surgery, could not be located, especially in the oblique plane.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] With the advent of 3D ultrasound, the imaging technique has evolved such that it enables the surgeon to obtain a real-time picture of tissues and organs, visualizing the complete scan more efficiently.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] In addition, 3D ultrasound provides surgical guidance in organ transplantation and cancer treatment, especially by employing rotational visualizing during scan.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] Various methods are used in this area, including rotational scanning, slice projection, and the use of integrated array transducers.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] With 3D ultrasound, it is possible to treat a broader range of tumors, as more tissues can be diagnosed and inspected.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] Blood vessels and arteries are relatively difficult to image, due to their distribution.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] 3D ultrasound has made it easier to track the dynamic movement of blood cells, veins and arteries.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] Various types of diagnostic tasks can be achieved with 3D ultrasound, such as measuring blood vessel diameter and diagnosing arterial walls.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] Some of these tasks can be undertaken with a magnetic tracker, integrated with the ultrasound, which assists in accurate positioning.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] Real-time 3D ultrasound is used during peripheral nerve blockade procedures to identify the relevant anatomy and monitor the spread of local anesthetic around the nerve.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] Peripheral nerve blockades prevent the transmission of pain signals from the site of injury to the brain without deep sedation, which makes them particularly useful for outpatient orthopedic procedures.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] Real-time 3D ultrasound allows muscles, nerves and vessels to be clearly identified while a needle or catheter is advanced under the skin.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] This type of ultrasound is capable of imaging the needle regardless of the plane of the image, which is a substantial improvement over 2D ultrasound.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] Additionally, the image can be rotated or cropped in real time to reveal anatomical structures within a volume of tissue.
[src:abortion/3d-ultrasound] Physicians at the Mayo Clinic in Jacksonville have been developing techniques using real time 3D ultrasound to guide peripheral nerve blocks for shoulder, knee, and ankle surgery.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] Estimated and projected populations of the world and its continents (except Antarctica) from 1950.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] The shaded regions correspond to the range of projections by the United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] The Day of Seven Billion, October 31, 2011, is the day that has been officially designated by the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) as the approximate day on which the total world population reached a population of seven billion people.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon spoke at the United Nations building in New York City on this milestone in the size of world population about the issues that it will raise, along with promoting 7 Billion Actions.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] The 7 Billion Actions Campaign aims to raise awareness of key population issues such as reproductive health, poverty, women empowerment, youth, environment sustainability, ageing, and urbanization, by encouraging people to take action and recommit to humanity.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] The campaign will count and showcase 7 billion online and offline actions that tell the story of the people behind the number and the connections they share with each other and the issues they each face.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] The 7 Billion Actions Campaign centers on highlighting individuals and organizations making a significant impact and creating innovative solutions in the 7 key issues identified as most imperative for the growing global population.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] 7BillionActions.org: Showcases stories, interviews, and news.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] In-depth platform to help individuals connect and take action with efforts taking place near them or across the globe.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] Interactive data visualizations highlighting challenges and solutions.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] I Count: An online and SMS/mobile effort allowing anyone on Earth to step forward to be counted as one of the 7 billion and share what issues matters most to them.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] These are but a few of the important resources being created to facilitate connection and collaboration.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] World Story Book: A community-created collection of photos, text, audio, and video that tell the stories of struggle and success of the people behind the number.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] 7Billion Hashtag (#7Billion): An ongoing social media conversation on Twitter, Facebook, and other major social media platforms (representing each major region) designed to help fuel awareness, engagement, and participation.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] IBM: As a way to celebrate its 100th anniversary, IBM is launching its Global Celebration of Service, a worldwide volunteer service initiative which calls for staff to donate their time and energy to specific social causes.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] 7 Billion Actions will be presented as one of the official programs which staff can support.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] As part of the new partnership, IBM volunteers will contribute their engineering, marketing, communications, social media and analytics expertise to help build the 7 Billion Actions campaign platform.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] crowdSPRING: crowdSPRING launched a series of design competitions to crowd source the official logo for the 7 Billion Actions Campaign.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] The first round of the competition drew over one thousand submissions and the winning design will become the 7 Billion Action Campaign's official global logo.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] The next phase will open voting to the public in order to select a group of regionally themed logos.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] Blog Talk Radio: Using their telephone-to-internet platform, the 7 Billion Actions Campaign will launch the Conversations for a World at 7 Billion channel to showcase a variety of audio programs discussing the topics and themes facing the 7 billion.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] People in different countries and regions will have the opportunity listen to and call into these programs and share their stories and actions.
[src:abortion/7-billion-actions] Playing for Change: The non-profit group the Playing for Change Foundation will partner with 7 Billion Actions to produce an official campaign song.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] An **abdominal pregnancy** is a rare type of ectopic pregnancy where the embryo or fetus is growing and developing outside the uterus, in the abdomen, and not in a fallopian tube (usual location), an ovary, or the broad ligament.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Because tubal, ovarian and broad ligament pregnancies are as difficult to diagnose and treat as abdominal pregnancies, their exclusion from the most common definition of abdominal pregnancy has been debated.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Others—in the minority—are of the view that abdominal pregnancy should be defined by a placenta implanted into the peritoneum.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Symptoms may include abdominal pain or vaginal bleeding during pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] As this is nonspecific in areas where ultrasound is not available the diagnosis was often only discovered during surgery to investigate the abnormal symptoms.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] They are typically diagnosed later in the developing world than the developed.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] In about half of cases from a center in the developing world the diagnosis was initially missed.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] It is a dangerous condition as there can be bleeding into the abdomen that results in low blood pressure and can be fatal.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Other causes of death in women with an abdominal pregnancy include anemia, pulmonary embolus, coagulopathy, and infection.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Implantation sites can be anywhere in the abdomen but can include the peritoneum outside of the uterus, the rectouterine pouch (culdesac of Douglas), omentum, bowel and its mesentery, mesosalpinx, and the peritoneum of the pelvic wall and the abdominal wall.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] The growing placenta may be attached to several organs including tube and ovary.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Rare other sites have been the liver and spleen, giving rise to a hepatic pregnancy or splenic pregnancy, respectively.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Even an early diaphragmatic pregnancy has been described in a patient where an embryo began growing on the underside of the diaphragm.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] A primary abdominal pregnancy refers to a pregnancy that first implanted directly in the peritoneum, save for the tubes and ovaries; such pregnancies are very rare, only 24 cases having been reported by 2007.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Typically an abdominal pregnancy is a secondary implantation which means that it originated from a tubal (less common an ovarian) pregnancy and re-implanted.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Other mechanisms for secondary abdominal pregnancy include uterine rupture, rupture of a uterine rudimentary horn and fimbrial abortion.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Suspicion of an abdominal pregnancy is raised when the fetal anatomy can be easily felt, or the lie is abnormal, the cervix is displaced, or there is failed induction of labor.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] MRI has also been used with success to diagnose abdominal pregnancy and plan for surgery.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Elevated alpha-fetoprotein levels are another clue of the presence of an abdominal pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Most cases can be diagnosed by ultrasound.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] The diagnosis however may be missed with ultrasound depending on the operator's skill.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Studdiford's criteria were refined in 1968 by Friedrich and Rankin to include microscopic findings.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Depending on gestational age the differential diagnoses for abdominal pregnancy include miscarriage, intrauterine fetal death, placental abruption, an acute abdomen with an intrauterine pregnancy and a fibroid uterus with an intrauterine pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Ideally the management of abdominal pregnancy should be done by a team that has medical personnel from multiple specialties.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Potential treatments consist of surgery with termination of the pregnancy (removal of the fetus) via laparoscopy or laparotomy, use of methotrexate, embolization, and combinations of these.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] The choice is largely dictated by the clinical situation.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Generally, treatment is indicated when the diagnosis is made; however, the situation of the advanced abdominal pregnancy is more complicated.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Advanced abdominal pregnancy refers to situations where the pregnancy continues past 20 weeks of gestation (versus early abdominal pregnancy < 20 weeks).
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] In those situations, live births have been reported in the lay press where the babies are not uncommonly referred to as 'miracle babies'.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] A patient may carry a dead fetus but will not go into labor.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Over time, the fetus calcifies and becomes a lithopedion.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] It is generally recommended to perform a laparotomy when the diagnosis of an abdominal pregnancy is made.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] However, if the baby is alive and medical support systems are in place, careful watching could be considered to bring the baby to viability.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Women with an abdominal pregnancy will not go into labor.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Delivery in a case of an advanced abdominal pregnancy will have to be via laparotomy.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] The survival of the baby is reduced and high perinatal mortality rates between 40% and 95% have been reported.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Babies of abdominal pregnancies are prone to birth defects due to compression in the absence of the uterine wall and the often reduced amount of amniotic fluid surrounding the unborn baby.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] The rate of malformations and deformations is estimated to be about 21%; typical deformations are facial and cranial asymmetries and joint abnormalities and the most common malformations are limb defects and central nervous malformations.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Once the baby has been delivered placental management becomes an issue.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] In normal deliveries the contraction of uterus provides a powerful mechanism to control blood loss, however, in an abdominal pregnancy the placenta is located over tissue that cannot contract and attempts of its removal may lead to life-threatening blood loss.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Thus blood transfusion is frequent in the management of patients with this kind of pregnancy, with others even using tranexamic acid and recombinant factor VIIa, which both minimize blood loss.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Generally, unless the placenta can be easily tied off or removed, it may be preferable to leave it in place and allow for a natural regression.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] This process may take several months and can be monitored by clinical examination, checking human chorionic gonadotropin levels and by ultrasound scanning (in particular using doppler ultrasonography.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Use of methotrexate to accelerate placental regression is controversial as the large amount of necrotic tissue is a potential site for infection, mifepristone has also been used to promote placental regression.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Placental vessels have also been blocked by angiographic embolization.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Complications of leaving the placenta can include residual bleeding, infection, bowel obstruction, pre-eclampsia (which may all necessitate further surgery) and failure to breast feed due to placental hormones.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Outcome with abdominal pregnancy can be good for the baby and mother; Lampe described an abdominal pregnancy baby and her mother who were well more than 22 years after surgery.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] About 1.4% of ectopic pregnancies are abdominal, or about 1 out of every 8,000 pregnancies.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] A report from Nigeria places the frequency in that country at 34 per 100,000 deliveries and a report from Zimbabwe, 11 per 100,000 deliveries.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] The maternal mortality rate is estimated to be about 5 per 1,000 cases, about seven times the rate for ectopics in general, and about 90 times the rate for a "normal" delivery (1987 US data).
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Because pregnancy is outside the uterus, abdominal pregnancy serves as a model of human male pregnancy or for females who lack a uterus, although such pregnancy would be dangerous.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Abdominal pregnancy has served to further clarify the disease pre-eclampsia which was previously thought (1980s) to require a uterus for it to occur, however pre-eclampsia's occurrence in abdominal pregnancy (with the conceptus outside the uterus) helped throw light on pre-eclampsia's etiology.
[src:abortion/abdominal-pregnancy] Cases of combined simultaneous abdominal and intrauterine pregnancy have been reported.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] An **abortifacient** ("that which will cause a miscarriage" from Latin: *abortus* "miscarriage" and *faciens* "making") is a substance that induces abortion.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] This is a nonspecific term which may refer to any number of substances or medications, ranging from herbs to prescription medications.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Common abortifacients used in performing medical abortions include mifepristone, which is typically used in conjunction with misoprostol in a two-step approach.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Synthetic oxytocin, which is routinely used safely during term labor, is also commonly used to induce abortion in the second or third trimester.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] For thousands of years, writers in many parts of the world have described and recommended herbal abortifacients to women who seek to terminate a pregnancy, although their use may carry risks to the health of the woman.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Because "abortifacient" is a broad term used to describe a substance's effects on pregnancy, there is a wide range of drugs that can be described as abortifacients or as having abortifacient properties.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] The most commonly recommended medication regimen for intentionally inducing abortion involves the use of mifepristone followed by misoprostol one to two days later.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] The use of these medications for the purpose of ending a pregnancy has been extensively studied, and has been shown to be both effective and safe with fewer than 0.4% of patients needing hospitalization to treat an infection or to receive a blood transfusion.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] This combination is approved for use up to 10 weeks' gestation (70 days after the start of the last menstrual period).
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Other drugs with abortifacient properties can have multiple uses.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Both synthetic oxytocin (Pitocin) and dinoprostone (Cervidil, Prepidil) are routinely used during healthy, term labor.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Pitocin is used to induce and strengthen contractions, and Cervidil is used to prepare the cervix for labor by inducing softening and widening of this opening to the uterus.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] When used this way, neither medication is considered an abortifacient.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] However, the same drugs can be used to induce an abortion, particularly after 12 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Misoprostol (discussed above) is also used to treat peptic ulcers in patients who have had gastric or intestinal damage from use of NSAIDs.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Because its use in treatment of ulcers makes it easier to access, misoprostol alone is sometimes used for self-induced abortion in countries or regions where legal abortion is not available or readily accessible.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Not all abortifacient agents are taken with the intention to end a pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Methotrexate, a drug often used for management of rheumatoid arthritis, can induce abortion.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] For this reason contraception is often advised while using methotrexate for management of a chronic condition.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Sometimes herbs or herbal medicines are used in an attempt to induce abortion; use of such substances as abortifacients is dangerous, can cause serious‍— even lethal‍— side effects, and is not recommended by physicians.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] In general, a dose sufficient to be effective poses a risk to the mother because of potential liver and kidney damage; failed attempts may require a follow-up clinical abortion because the uterus did not evacuate completely.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Modern users often lack knowledge of the traditional methods of preparation and use of these substances.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Riddle called these circumstances a "broken chain of knowledge", one he attributed to the historic persecution of women acting as witches, midwives, or wisewomen who had knowledge of such practices.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] In ancient Babylonian texts, scholars have described multiple written prescriptions or instructions for ending pregnancies.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Some of these instructions were explicitly for ingesting ingredients to end a pregnancy, whereas other cuneiform texts discuss the ingestion of ingredients to return a missed menstrual period (which is used repeatedly throughout history as a coded reference to abortion).
[src:abortion/abortifacient] The ancient Greek colony of Cyrene at one time had an economy based almost entirely on the production and export of the plant silphium, which had uses ranging from food to a salve for feral dog bites.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] It was also considered a powerful abortifacient used to "purge the uterus".
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Silphium figured so prominently in the wealth of Cyrene that the plant appeared on coins minted there.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] In the Bible, Biblical scholars and learned Biblical commentators view the ordeal of the bitter water (prescribed for a *sotah*, or a wife whose husband suspects that she was unfaithful to him) as referring to the use of abortifacients to terminate her pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] The wife drinks "water of bitterness," which, if she is guilty, causes the abortion or miscarriage of a pregnancy she may be carrying.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] The Biblical scholar Tikva Frymer-Kensky has disputed the interpretation that the ordeal of the bitter water referred to the use of abortifacients.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] The medieval Islamic physician Ibn Sina documented various birth control practices, including the use of rue as an abortifacient.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Similarly, 11th-century physician Constantine the African described multiple abortifacient herbs, which he classified by order of their intensity, starting with abortifacients that had weaker effects on the body and ending with the most potent substances.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Carl Linnaeus, known as the "father of botany", listed five abortifacients in his 1749 *Materia medica*.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] For Aboriginal people in Australia, plants such as giant boat-lip orchid (*Cymbidium madidum*), quinine bush (*Petalostigma pubescens*), or blue-leaved mallee (*Eucalyptus gamophylla*) were ingested, inserted into the body, or were smoked with Cooktown ironwood (*Erythrophleum chlorostachys*).
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Historically, the First Nations people of eastern Canada used *Sanguinaria canadensis* (bloodwort) and *Juniperus virginiana* to induce abortions.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] According to Virgil Vogel, a historian of the indigenous societies of North America, the Ojibwe used blue cohosh (*Caulophyllum thalictroides*) as an abortifacient, and the Quinault used thistle for the same purpose.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] The appendix to Vogel's book lists red cedar (*Juniperus virginiana*), American pennyroyal (*Hedeoma pulegioides*), tansy, Canada wild ginger (*Asarum canadense*), and several other herbs as abortifacients used by various North American Indian tribes.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Following a tradition among European and English authors, colonial Americans were advised by Benjamin Franklin to use careful measurements in his recipe for an abortifacient that he used as an example in a book he published to teach mathematics and many useful skills.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] During the American slavery period, 18th and 19th centuries, cotton root bark was used in folk remedies to induce a miscarriage.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] In the late 19th century, women in the UK and US increasingly ingested lead to abort pregnancies, sometimes in the form of pills made of diachylon or lead plaster.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] It would often cause the women to become ill and could kill them.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] In the 19th century Madame Restell provided mail-order abortifacients and surgical abortion to pregnant clients in New York.
[src:abortion/abortifacient] Early 20th-century newspaper advertisements included coded advertisements for abortifacient substances which would solve menstrual "irregularities" .
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The **abortion–breast cancer hypothesis** posits that having an induced abortion can increase the risk of getting breast cancer.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] This hypothesis is at odds with mainstream scientific opinion and is rejected by major medical professional organizations; despite this, it continues to be widely propagated as pseudoscience, typically in service of an anti-abortion agenda.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] In early pregnancy, hormone levels increase, leading to breast growth.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The hypothesis proposes that if this process is altered by an abortion, then more immature cells could be left behind, and that these immature cells could increase the risk of breast cancer over time.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The abortion–breast cancer hypothesis has been the subject of extensive scientific inquiry, and the scientific community has concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer; and that breast cancer should not be a concern for women who are having a miscarriage or considering having an abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] This consensus is supported by major medical bodies, including the World Health Organization, the U.S.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] National Cancer Institute, the American Cancer Society, the American Congress of Obstetricians and Gynecologists, the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists, the German Cancer Research Center, and the Canadian Cancer Society.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Some anti-abortion activists have continued to advance a discredited causal link between abortion and breast cancer.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] In the United States, they have advanced state legislation that in several states requires health care providers to present abortion as a cause of breast cancer when counseling women who are seeking abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] This political intervention culminated when the George W.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Bush administration altered the National Cancer Institute website to suggest that abortion might cause breast cancer.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] In response to public concern over this intervention, the NCI convened a 2003 workshop bringing together over 100 experts on the issue.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The ongoing promotion of a link between abortion and breast cancer is seen by others as part of the anti-abortion "woman-centered" strategy against abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Anti-abortion groups maintain they are providing information necessary for legally required informed consent, a concern shared by some politically conservative politicians.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The abortion–breast cancer issue remains the subject of political controversy.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Major medical organizations which have analyzed data on abortion and breast cancer have uniformly concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] These organizations include the World Health Organization, the U.S.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Joel Brind, a faculty member at Baruch College in the Department of Natural Sciences, is the primary advocate of an abortion–breast cancer ("ABC") link.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Brind is strongly anti-abortion and began lobbying politicians with the claim that abortion caused breast cancer in the early 1990s.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Brind found that his lobbying efforts were not taken seriously because he had not published his findings in the peer-reviewed medical literature.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] He therefore collaborated with two anti-abortion physicians and a statistician to publish a 1996 article in the *Journal of Epidemiology and Community Health*, arguing that induced abortion was a risk factor for breast cancer.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The statistician who collaborated with Brind later stated of their findings: "I have some doubts.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] I don't think the issue has been resolved.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] When we were talking about the conclusions, he [Brind] wanted to make the strongest statements.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] I tried to temper them a little bit, but Dr.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Brind's paper was criticized in the *Journal of the National Cancer Institute* for ignoring the role of response bias and for a "blurring of association with causation." The amount of attention the study received prompted a cautionary editorial by a JECH editor.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] With the appearance of larger studies contradicting Brind's finding, Brind failed to convince the scientific community that abortion caused breast cancer.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] In 2003, Brind was invited to the NCI workshop on abortion and breast cancer, where he was the only one to formally dissent from the workshop's finding that there is no link between the two.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Brind blames the lack of support for his findings on a conspiracy, arguing that the NCI and other major medical organizations are engaged in a "cover-up" for the purpose of "protecting the abortion industry".
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] In early pregnancy, levels of estrogen, progesterone, and estradiol increase, leading to breast growth in preparation for lactation.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Proponents speculate that if this process is interrupted by an abortion or miscarriage—before full maturity (differentiation) in the third trimester—then more immature cells could be left than there were prior to the pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] These immature cells could then be exposed to carcinogens and hormones over time, resulting in a greater potential risk of breast cancer.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] This mechanism was first proposed and explored in rat studies conducted in the 1980s.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Breast tissue contains many lobes (segments) and these contain lobules which are groups of breast cells.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] During early pregnancy, type 1 lobules quickly become type 2 lobules because of changes in estrogen and progesterone levels.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Maturing into type 3 and then reaching full differentiation as type 4 lobules requires an increase of human placental lactogen (hPL) which occurs in the last few months of pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] According to the abortion–breast cancer hypothesis, if an abortion were to interrupt this sequence then it could leave a higher ratio of type 2 lobules than existed prior to the pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Later on, Russo *et al.* found that placental human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) induces the synthesis of inhibin by the mammary epithelium.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Bernstein *et al.* independently observed a reduced breast cancer risk when women were injected with hCG for weight loss or infertility treatment.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The first study involving statistics on abortion and breast cancer was a broad study in 1957 examining common cancers in Japan.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The researchers were cautious about drawing any conclusions from their unreliable methodologies.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] During the 1960s several studies by Brian MacMahon *et al.* in Europe and Asia touched on a correlation between abortion and breast cancer.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Russo & Russo from the Fox Chase Cancer Center in Philadelphia conducted a study in 1980 examining the proposed correlation between abortion and breast cancer.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] However, they did find that pregnancy and lactation provided a protective measure against various forms of benign lesions, such as hyperplastic alveolar nodules and cysts.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] While results did suggest that rats who had interrupted pregnancies might be subject to "similar or even higher incidence of benign lesions" than virgin rats, there was no evidence to suggest that abortion would result in a higher incidence of carcinogenesis.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] A more thorough examination of the phenomenon was conducted in 1982, confirming the results.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] A later study in 1987 further explained their previous findings.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] After differentiation of the mammary gland resulting from a full-term pregnancy of the rat, the rate of cell division decreases and the cell cycle length increases, allowing more time for DNA repair.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Despite the fact that the Russos' studies found similar risk rates between virgin and pregnancy interrupted rats, their research would be used to support the contention that abortion created a greater risk of breast cancer for the next twenty years.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] However, because rats do not exhibit naturally occurring breast cancer, the extrapolation of these results to human abortion and breast cancer is viewed as dubious.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The results of prospective cohort studies on the relationship between abortion and breast cancer have been consistently negative.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Such studies are considered more reliable than retrospective studies and case-control studies.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The positive association between abortion and breast cancer risk observed in case-control studies may be accounted for by recall bias.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] In 1996, Brind et al. published a meta-analysis of 23 studies which reported a positive association existed between induced abortion and breast cancer risk.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The authors estimated the relative risk of breast cancer among women who had had an induced abortion to be 1.3, compared to women who had not had an abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] It was criticized by other researchers for multiple reasons, including allegations that it failed to account for publication bias (positive studies tend to be more likely to be published).
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The meta-analysis was also criticized because the studies it included were almost all case-control studies, which are susceptible to recall bias, and for which it is difficult to select an appropriate control group.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] In 1997, Wingo et al. reviewed 32 studies on the abortion-breast cancer relationship and concluded that the results of studies on this subject were too inconsistent to allow for definitive conclusions, for either induced or spontaneous abortions.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] A 2004 analysis of data from 53 studies involving 83,000 women with breast cancer reported no increased risk among women who had had either an induced or spontaneous abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The relative risk of breast cancer for women who had a spontaneous abortion in this analysis was 0.98, and that for induced abortion was 0.93.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] A 2015 systematic review and meta-analysis of prospective studies found insufficient evidence to support an association between induced or spontaneous abortion and an increased risk of breast cancer.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] By the late 1980s, national politicians recognized that a focus on reducing access to abortion was not a winning political strategy.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Some anti-abortion activists grew more aggressive and violent in the face of political abandonment, culminating with the murder of Dr.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] David Gunn in 1993 and the passage of the Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act in 1994.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] With direct action discredited, anti-abortion organizations, including the National Right to Life Committee, came to the forefront of the movement.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] These focused on legal tactics, including lobbying against late-term abortions and access to mifepristone and demanding legislation based on the purported ABC link.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] More recently, anti-abortion organizations have turned to lobbying to increase obstacles to abortion, such as mandated counseling, waiting periods, and parental notification, and some feel that anti-abortion advocates treat ABC as simply another tactic in their campaign against abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] There have been ongoing and incremental legal challenges to abortion in the United States by anti-abortion groups.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] In 2005, a Canadian anti-abortion organization put up billboards in Alberta with large pink ribbons and the statement: "Stop the Cover-Up", in reference to the ABC hypothesis.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The Canadian Breast Cancer Foundation was concerned by the misrepresentation of the state of scientific knowledge on the subject.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The continued focus on the ABC hypothesis by anti-abortion groups has fostered a confrontational political environment.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Anti-abortion advocates and scientists alike have responded with criticisms.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The claims by anti-abortion advocates are sometimes referred to as pseudoscience.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] During the late 1990s, several members of the United States Congress became involved in the ABC issue.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] In a 1998 hearing on cancer research, U.S.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Representative Tom Coburn accused the National Cancer Institute of misleading the public by selectively releasing data.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] In 1999, shortly after the House debated FDA approval of the abortion drug mifepristone, U.S.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Representative Dave Weldon wrote a "Dear Colleague" letter, enclosing an article from John Kindley.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] As of 2019, abortion counseling materials in Alaska, Kansas, Mississippi, Oklahoma, and Texas incorrectly assert a possible link between abortion and breast cancer, while Minnesota materials correctly report no link.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Similar legislation requiring notification has also been introduced in 14 other states.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] An editor for the *American Journal of Public Health* expressed concern that these bills propose warnings that do not agree with established scientific findings.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Appel argues that the mandatory disclosure statutes might be unconstitutional on "rational basis" grounds.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Childbirth is significantly more dangerous than abortion, data that is not required in any disclosure law but which is necessary for a meaningful understanding of risks.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] According to Appel, "[i]f the roughly fifty million abortions that have occurred in the United States since *Roe v.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] In May 2017, President Donald Trump appointed Charmaine Yoest, an anti-abortion activist and proponent of the abortion-breast cancer link, to the post of assistant secretary for public affairs in the Department of Health And Human Services.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The National Cancer Institute (NCI) has been a target of the anti-abortion movement for the conclusions presented on its website.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] A report from the Committee on Oversight and Government Reform found that in November 2002 the Bush administration had altered the NCI website.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The previous NCI analysis had concluded that, while some question regarding an association between abortion and breast cancer existed prior to the mid-1990s, a number of large and well-regarded studies had resolved the issue in the negative.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] This alteration, which suggested that there was scientific uncertainty on the ABC issue, prompted an editorial in *The New York Times* describing it as an "egregious distortion" and a letter to the Secretary of Health and Human Services from members of Congress.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] In response to the alteration the NCI convened a three-day consensus workshop entitled *Early Reproductive Events and Breast Cancer* on 24–26 February 2003.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The workshop concluded that induced abortion does not increase a woman's risk of breast cancer, and that the evidence for this had been well established.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Afterwards, the director of epidemiology research for the American Cancer Society stated, "[t]his issue has been resolved scientifically ...
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Brind was the only attendee at the workshop to file a dissenting opinion as a minority report criticizing the conclusions.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] He contends the workshop evidence and findings were overly controlled by its organizers and that the time allotted was too short for a thorough review of the literature.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] In January 2000, Amy Jo Kjolsrud (née Mattson), an anti-abortion counselor, sued the Red River Women's Clinic in Fargo, North Dakota, alleging false advertising.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] MKB Management Corporation*, alleged that the clinic was misleading women by distributing a brochure quoting a National Cancer Institute fact sheet on the ABC hypothesis.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The case was originally scheduled for 11 September 2001, but was delayed as a result of the terrorist attacks.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] After four days of testimony, Judge Michael McGuire ruled in favor of the clinic.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Linda Rosenthal, an attorney from the Center for Reproductive Rights characterized the decision as a rejection of "scare tactics".
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] John Kindley, one of the lawyers representing Kjolsrud, highlighted the "individual's right to self-determination".
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] Kindley also wrote a 1998 *Wisconsin Law Review* article outlining the viability of medical malpractice lawsuits based upon not informing patients considering abortion about the ABC hypothesis.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The decision was appealed and on 23 September 2003 the North Dakota Supreme Court ruled that Kjolsrud did not have standing and affirmed the lower court ruling dismissing the action.
[src:abortion/abortion-breast-cancer-hypothesis] The appeal said that Kjolsrud had not read the materials, and that after the lawsuit was filed, the brochures were updated to refute the breast cancer link, citing the National Cancer Institute.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] When done legally in industrialized societies, induced abortion is one of the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Modern methods use medication or surgery for abortions.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The drug mifepristone (aka RU-486) in combination with prostaglandin appears to be as safe and effective as surgery during the first and second trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Self-managed medication abortion is highly effective and safe throughout the first trimester.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The most common surgical technique involves dilating the cervix and using a suction device.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Birth control, such as contraceptive pills or intrauterine devices, can be used immediately following an abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] When performed legally and safely on a woman who desires it, an induced abortion does not increase the risk of long-term mental or physical problems.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In contrast, unsafe abortions performed by unskilled individuals, with hazardous equipment, or in unsanitary facilities cause between 22,000 and 44,000 deaths and 6.9 million hospital admissions each year — responsible for between 5% and 13% of maternal deaths, especially in low-income countries.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization states that "access to legal, safe and comprehensive abortion care, including post-abortion care, is essential for the attainment of the highest possible level of sexual and reproductive health".
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Public health data show that making safe abortion legal and accessible reduces maternal deaths.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Around 73 million abortions are performed each year in the world, with about 45% done unsafely.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Abortion rates changed little between 2003 and 2008, before which they decreased for at least two decades as access to family planning and birth control increased.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] As of 2018, 37% of the world's women had access to legal abortions without limits as to reason.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Countries that permit abortions have different limits on how late in pregnancy abortion is allowed.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Abortion rates are similar between countries that restrict abortion and countries that broadly allow it, though this is partly because countries which restrict abortion tend to have higher unintended pregnancy rates.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Since 1973, there has been a global trend towards greater legal access to abortion, but there remains debate with regard to moral, religious, ethical, and legal issues.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Those who oppose abortion often argue that an embryo or fetus is a person with a right to life, and thus equate abortion with murder.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Those who support abortion's legality often argue that it is a woman's reproductive right.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Others favor legal and accessible abortion as a public health measure.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Abortion laws and views of the procedure are different around the world.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In some countries abortion is legal and women have the right to make the choice about abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In some areas, abortion is legal only in specific cases such as rape, incest, fetal defects, poverty, and risk to a woman's health.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Historically, abortions have been attempted using herbal medicines, sharp tools, forceful massage, or other traditional methods.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] An induced abortion is a medical procedure to end a pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In present-day English, the term *abortion*, when used without further qualification, generally refers to induced abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A pregnancy can be intentionally aborted in several ways.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The abortion method depends upon the gestational age of the embryo or fetus, which gains mass as the pregnancy progresses.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Abortion laws, regional availability, and the personal preference of the woman and her doctor may inform the woman's choice of a specific abortion procedure.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Abortions can be characterized as either therapeutic or elective.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] When an abortion is performed for medical reasons, the procedure is referred to as a therapeutic abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] An abortion is referred to as elective or voluntary when it is performed at the request of the woman for non-medical reasons.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Confusion sometimes arises over the term *elective* because "elective surgery" generally refers to all scheduled surgery, whether medically necessary or not.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] About one in five pregnancies worldwide ends with an induced abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Most abortions result from unintended pregnancies.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In the United Kingdom, 1 to 2% of abortions are done because of genetic problems in the fetus.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Miscarriage, also known as spontaneous abortion, is the unintentional expulsion of an embryo or fetus before the 24th week of gestation.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A pregnancy that ends before 37 weeks of gestation resulting in a live-born infant is a "premature birth" or a "preterm birth".
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] When a fetus dies in utero after viability, or during delivery, it is usually termed "stillborn".
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Premature births and stillbirths are generally not considered to be miscarriages, although usage of these terms can sometimes overlap.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Studies of pregnant women in the US and China have shown that between 40% and 60% of embryos do not progress to birth.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The vast majority of miscarriages occur before the woman is aware that she is pregnant, and many pregnancies spontaneously abort before medical practitioners can detect an embryo.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Between 15% and 30% of known pregnancies end in clinically apparent miscarriage, depending upon the age and health of the pregnant woman.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] 80% of these spontaneous abortions happen in the first trimester.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The most common cause of spontaneous abortion during the first trimester is chromosomal abnormalities of the embryo or fetus, accounting for at least 50% of sampled early pregnancy losses.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Other causes include vascular disease (such as lupus), diabetes, other hormonal problems, infection, and abnormalities of the uterus.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Advancing maternal age and a woman's history of previous spontaneous abortions are the two leading factors associated with a greater risk of spontaneous abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A spontaneous abortion can also be caused by accidental trauma; intentional trauma or stress to cause miscarriage is considered induced abortion or feticide.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] may determine which abortion methods are practiced.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Medical abortions are those induced by abortifacient pharmaceuticals.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Medical abortion became an alternative method of abortion with the availability of prostaglandin analogs in the 1970s and the antiprogestogen mifepristone (also known as RU-486) in the 1980s.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimens work faster and are more effective at later gestational ages than methotrexate–misoprostol combination regimens, and combination regimens are more effective than misoprostol alone, particularly in the second trimester.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Medical abortion regimens involving mifepristone followed by misoprostol in the cheek between 24 and 48 hours later are effective when performed before 70 days' gestation.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In very early abortions, up to 7 weeks gestation, medical abortion using a mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimen is considered to be more effective than surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration), especially when clinical practice does not include detailed inspection of aspirated tissue.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Early medical abortion regimens using mifepristone, followed 24–48 hours later by buccal or vaginal misoprostol are 98% effective up to 9 weeks gestational age; from 9 to 10 weeks efficacy decreases modestly to 94%.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] If medical abortion fails, surgical abortion must be used to complete the procedure.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Early medical abortions account for the majority of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in Britain, France, Switzerland, United States, and the Nordic countries.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A 2020 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that providing women with medications to take home to complete the second stage of the procedure for an early medical abortion results in an effective abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Further research is required to determine if self-administered medical abortion is as safe as provider-administered medical abortion, where a health care professional is present to help manage the medical abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Safely permitting women to self-administer abortion medication has the potential to improve access to abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The review also noted a research gap concerning methods to support women who take medication at home for a self-administered abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Up to 15 weeks' gestation, suction-aspiration or vacuum aspiration are the most common surgical methods of induced abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] *Manual vacuum aspiration* (MVA) consists of removing the fetus or embryo, placenta, and membranes by suction using a manual syringe, while *electric vacuum aspiration* (EVA) uses an electric pump.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Both techniques can be used very early in pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] MVA can be used up to 14 weeks but is more often used earlier in the U.S.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] MVA, also known as "mini-suction" and "menstrual extraction", or EVA can be used in very early pregnancy when cervical dilation may not be required.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Dilation and curettage (D&C) refers to opening the cervix (dilation) and removing tissue (curettage) via suction or sharp instruments.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] D&C is a standard gynecological procedure performed for a variety of reasons, including examination of the uterine lining for possible malignancy, investigation of abnormal bleeding, and abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization recommends *sharp curettage* only when suction aspiration is unavailable.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Dilation and evacuation (D&E), used after 12 to 16 weeks, consists of opening the cervix and removing pregnancy tissue and fetal parts with suction and forceps.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] D&E is performed vaginally and does not require an incision.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Intact dilation and extraction (D&X) refers to a variant of D&E sometimes used after 18 to 20 weeks when removal of an intact fetus improves surgical safety or for other reasons.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Abortion may also be performed surgically by hysterotomy or gravid hysterectomy.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy abortion is a procedure similar to a caesarean section and is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] It requires a smaller incision than a caesarean section and can be used during later stages of pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Gravid hysterectomy refers to removal of the whole uterus while still containing the pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy and hysterectomy are associated with much higher rates of maternal morbidity and mortality than D&E or induction abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] First trimester procedures can generally be performed using local anesthesia, while second trimester methods may require deep sedation or general anesthesia.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In places lacking the necessary medical skill for dilation and extraction, or when preferred by practitioners, an abortion can be induced by first inducing labor and then inducing fetal demise if necessary.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] This is sometimes called "induced miscarriage".
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] This procedure may be performed from 13 weeks gestation to the third trimester.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Although it is very uncommon in the United States, more than 80% of induced abortions throughout the second trimester are labor-induced abortions in Sweden and other nearby countries.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Only limited data are available comparing labor-induced abortion with the dilation and extraction method.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Unlike D&E, labor-induced abortions after 18 weeks may be complicated by the occurrence of brief fetal survival, which may be legally characterized as live birth.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] For this reason, labor-induced abortion is legally risky in the United States.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Historically, a number of herbs reputed to possess abortifacient properties have been used in folk medicine.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Such herbs include tansy, pennyroyal, black cohosh, and the now-extinct silphium.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In 1978, one woman in Colorado died and another developed organ damage when they attempted to terminate their pregnancies by taking pennyroyal oil.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Because the indiscriminant use of herbs as abortifacients can cause serious—even lethal—side effects, such as multiple organ failure, such use is not recommended by physicians.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Abortion is sometimes attempted by causing trauma to the abdomen.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The degree of force, if severe, can cause serious internal injuries without necessarily succeeding in inducing miscarriage.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In Southeast Asia, there is an ancient tradition of attempting abortion through forceful abdominal massage.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] One of the bas reliefs decorating the temple of Angkor Wat in Cambodia depicts a demon performing such an abortion upon a woman who had been sent to the underworld.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Reported methods of unsafe, self-induced abortion include misuse of misoprostol and insertion of non-surgical implements such as knitting needles and clothes hangers into the uterus.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] These and other methods to terminate pregnancy may be called "induced miscarriage".
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Such methods are rarely used in countries where surgical abortion is legal and available.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The health risks of abortion depend principally on how, and under what conditions, the procedure is performed.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) defines unsafe abortions as a procedure for terminating an unintended pregnancy carried out either by persons lacking the necessary skills or in an environment that does not conform to minimal medical standards, or both.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Legal abortions performed in the developed world are among the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] According to a 2012 study in *Obstetrics & Gynecology*, in the United States the risk of maternal mortality is 14 times lower after induced abortion than after childbirth.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The CDC estimated in 2019 that US pregnancy-related mortality was 17.2 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births, while the US abortion mortality rate was 0.43 maternal deaths per 100,000 procedures.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In the UK, guidelines of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists state that "Women should be advised that abortion is generally safer than continuing a pregnancy to term." Worldwide, on average, abortion is safer than carrying a pregnancy to term.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In the US from 2000 to 2009, abortion had a mortality rate lower than plastic surgery, lower or similar to running a marathon, and about equivalent to traveling 760 miles (1,220 km) in a passenger car.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Outpatient abortion is as safe from 64 to 70 days' gestation as it before 63 days.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A 2019 study indicated that five years after seeking abortion services, women who gave birth after being denied an abortion reported worse health than women who had either first or second trimester abortions.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] There is little difference in terms of safety and efficacy between medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol and surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration) in early first trimester abortions up to 10 weeks gestation.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Medical abortion using the prostaglandin analog misoprostol alone is less effective and more painful than medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol or surgical abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Vacuum aspiration in the first trimester is the safest method of surgical abortion, and can be performed in a primary care office, abortion clinic, or hospital.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Complications, which are rare, can include uterine perforation, pelvic infection, and retained products of conception requiring a second procedure to evacuate.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Infections account for one-third of abortion-related deaths in the United States.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The rate of complications of vacuum aspiration abortion in the first trimester is similar regardless of whether the procedure is performed in a hospital, surgical center, or office.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Preventive antibiotics (such as doxycycline or metronidazole) are typically given before abortion procedures, as they are believed to substantially reduce the risk of postoperative uterine infection; however, antibiotics are not routinely given with abortion pills.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The rate of failed procedures does not appear to vary significantly depending on whether the abortion is performed by a doctor or a mid-level practitioner.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Complications after second trimester abortion are similar to those after first trimester abortion, and depend somewhat on the method chosen.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The risk of death from abortion approaches roughly half the risk of death from childbirth the farther along a woman is in pregnancy; from one in a million before 9 weeks gestation to nearly one in ten thousand at 21 weeks or more (as measured from the last menstrual period).
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] It appears that having had a prior surgical uterine evacuation (whether because of induced abortion or treatment of miscarriage) correlates with a small increase in the risk of preterm birth in future pregnancies.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The studies supporting this did not control for factors not related to abortion or miscarriage, and hence the causes of this correlation have not been determined, although multiple possibilities have been suggested.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Current evidence finds no relationship between most induced abortions and mental health problems other than those expected for any unwanted pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Some older reviews concluded that abortion was associated with an increased risk of psychological problems; however, later reviews of the medical literature found that previous reviews did not use an appropriate control group.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] When a control group is utilized, receiving abortion is not associated with adverse psychological outcomes.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] However, women seeking abortion who are denied access to abortion have an increase in anxiety after the denial.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Although some studies show negative mental-health outcomes in women who choose abortions after the first trimester because of fetal abnormalities, more rigorous research would be needed to show this conclusively.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Some proposed negative psychological effects of abortion have been referred to by anti-abortion advocates as a separate condition called "post-abortion syndrome", but this is not recognized by medical or psychological professionals in the United States.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A 2020 long term-study among US women found that about 99% of women felt that they made the right decision five years after they had an abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Relief was the primary emotion with few women feeling sadness or guilt.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Social stigma was a main factor predicting negative emotions and regret years later.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Some purported risks of abortion are promoted primarily by anti-abortion groups, but lack scientific support.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] For example, the question of a link between induced abortion and breast cancer has been investigated extensively.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Major medical and scientific bodies (including the WHO, National Cancer Institute, American Cancer Society, Royal College of OBGYN and American Congress of OBGYN) have concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In the past even illegality has not automatically meant that the abortions were unsafe.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A 1940s American physician spoke of his pride in having performed 13,844 illegal abortions without any fatalities.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In 1870s New York City, the abortionist/midwife Madame Restell (Anna Trow Lohman) is said to have lost very few women among her more than 100,000 patients—a lower mortality rate than the childbirth mortality rate at the time.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In 1936, obstetrics and gynecology professor Frederick J.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Women seeking an abortion may use unsafe methods, especially when abortion is legally restricted.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] They may attempt self-induced abortion or seek the help of a person without proper medical training or facilities.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] This can lead to severe complications, such as incomplete abortion, sepsis, hemorrhage, and damage to internal organs.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are a major cause of injury and death among women worldwide.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Although data are imprecise, it is estimated that approximately 20 million unsafe abortions are performed annually, with 97% taking place in developing countries.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are believed to result in millions of injuries.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Estimates of deaths vary according to methodology, and have ranged from 37,000 to 70,000 in the past decade; deaths from unsafe abortion account for around 13% of all maternal deaths.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization believes that mortality has fallen since the 1990s.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] To reduce the number of unsafe abortions, public health organizations have generally advocated emphasizing the legalization of abortion, training of medical personnel, and ensuring access to reproductive-health services.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A major factor in whether abortions are performed safely or not is the legal standing of abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Countries with restrictive abortion laws have higher rates of unsafe abortion and similar overall abortion rates compared to countries where abortion is legal and available.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] For example, the 1996 legalization of abortion in South Africa led to an immediate reduction in abortion-related complications, with abortion-related deaths dropping by more than 90%.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Similar reductions in maternal mortality have been observed after other countries have liberalized their abortion laws, such as Romania and Nepal.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A 2011 study concluded that in the United States, some state-level anti-abortion laws are correlated with lower rates of abortion in that state.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The analysis, however, did not take into account travel to other states without such laws to obtain an abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In addition, a lack of access to effective contraception contributes to unsafe abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] It has been estimated that the incidence of unsafe abortion could be reduced by up to 75% (from 20 million to 5 million annually) if modern family planning and maternal health services were readily available globally.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Rates of such abortions may be difficult to measure because they can be reported variously as miscarriage, "induced miscarriage", "menstrual regulation", "mini-abortion", and "regulation of a delayed/suspended menstruation".
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Forty percent of the world's women are able to access therapeutic and elective abortions within gestational limits, while an additional 35 percent have access to legal abortion if they meet certain physical, mental, or socioeconomic criteria.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] While maternal mortality seldom results from safe abortions, unsafe abortions result in 70,000 deaths and 5 million disabilities per year.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Complications of unsafe abortion account for approximately an eighth of maternal mortalities worldwide, though this varies by region.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Secondary infertility caused by an unsafe abortion affects an estimated 24 million women.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The rate of unsafe abortions has increased from 44% to 49% between 1995 and 2008.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Health education, access to family planning, and improvements in health care during and after abortion have been proposed to address consequences of unsafe abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In many places, where abortion is illegal or carries a heavy social stigma, medical reporting of abortion is not reliable.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] For this reason, estimates of the incidence of abortion must be made without determining certainty related to standard error.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The number of abortions performed worldwide was characterized as stable in the early 2000s, with 41.6 million having been performed in 2003 and 43.8 million having been performed in 2008.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The abortion rate worldwide was 28 per 1000 women per year, though it was 24 per 1000 women per year for developed countries and 29 per 1000 women per year for developing countries.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The same 2012 study indicated that in 2008, the estimated abortion percentage of known pregnancies was at 21% worldwide, with 26% in developed countries and 20% in developing countries.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] On average, the incidence of abortion is similar in countries with restrictive abortion laws and those with more liberal access to abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Restrictive abortion laws are associated with increases in the percentage of abortions performed unsafely.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The rate of legal, induced abortion varies extensively worldwide.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] According to the report of employees of Guttmacher Institute it ranged from 7 per 1000 women per year (Germany and Switzerland) to 30 per 1000 women per year (Estonia) in countries with complete statistics in 2008.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The proportion of pregnancies that ended in induced abortion ranged from about 10% (Israel, the Netherlands and Switzerland) to 30% (Estonia) in the same group, though it might be as high as 36% in Hungary and Romania, whose statistics were deemed incomplete.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] An American study in 2002 concluded that about half of women having abortions were using a form of contraception at the time of becoming pregnant.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Inconsistent use was reported by half of those using condoms and three-quarters of those using the birth control pill; 42% of those using condoms reported failure through slipping or breakage.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Of the other half of women, who were not using contraception at the time of becoming pregnant, the vast majority had used contraception at some point in the past, indicating some level of dissatisfaction with the contraceptive options available to them.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Indeed, 32% of these contraceptive nonusers cited concerns about contraceptive methods as their reason for nonuse, and a more recent study found similar results.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Taken together, these statistics suggest that new contraceptive methods, such as non-hormonal contraceptives or male contraceptives, could reduce unintended pregnancy and abortion rates.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute has found that "most abortions in the United States are obtained by minority women" because minority women "have much higher rates of unintended pregnancy".
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] in England and Wales during 2019 (left).
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Abortion in the United States by gestational age, 2016 (right).
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Abortion rates vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and the method practiced.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] 91% of these were classified as having been done by "curettage" (suction-aspiration, dilation and curettage, dilation and evacuation), 8% by "medical" means (mifepristone), >1% by "intrauterine instillation" (saline or prostaglandin), and 1% by "other" (including hysterotomy and hysterectomy).
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] According to the CDC, due to data collection difficulties the data must be viewed as tentative and some fetal deaths reported beyond 20 weeks may be natural deaths erroneously classified as abortions if the removal of the dead fetus is accomplished by the same procedure as an induced abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute estimated there were 2,200 intact dilation and extraction procedures in the US during 2000; this accounts for <0.2% of the total number of abortions performed that year.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Similarly, in England and Wales in 2006, 89% of terminations occurred at or under 12 weeks, 9% between 13 and 19 weeks, and 2% at or over 20 weeks.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] 64% of those reported were by vacuum aspiration, 6% by D&E, and 30% were medical.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] There are more second trimester abortions in developing countries such as China, India and Vietnam than in developed countries.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] There are both medical and non-medical reasons to have an abortion later in pregnancy (after 20 weeks).
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A study was conducted from 2008 to 2010 at the University of California San Francisco where more than 440 women were asked about why they experienced delays in obtaining abortion care, if there were any.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] This study found that almost half of individuals who obtained an abortion after 20 weeks did not suspect that they were pregnant until later in their pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Other barriers to abortion care found in the study included lack of information about where to access an abortion, difficulties with transportation, lack of insurance coverage, and inability to pay for the abortion procedure.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Medical reasons for seeking an abortion later in pregnancy include fetal anomalies and health risk to the pregnant person.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] There are prenatal tests that can diagnose Down Syndrome or cystic fibrosis as early as 10 weeks into gestation, but structural fetal anomalies are often detected much later in pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A proportion of structural fetal anomalies are lethal, which means that the fetus will almost certainly die before or shortly after birth.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Life-threatening conditions may also develop later in pregnancy, such as early severe preeclampsia, newly diagnosed cancer in need of urgent treatment, and intrauterine infection (chorioamnionitis), which often occurs along with premature rupture of the amniotic sac (PPROM).
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] If serious medical conditions such as these arise before the fetus is viable, the person carrying the pregnancy may pursue an abortion to preserve their own health.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The reasons why women have abortions are diverse and vary across the world.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Some of the reasons may include an inability to afford a child, domestic violence, lack of support, feeling they are too young, and the wish to complete education or advance a career.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Additional reasons include not being able or willing to raise a child conceived as a result of rape or incest.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Some abortions are undergone as the result of societal pressures.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] These factors can sometimes result in compulsory abortion or sex-selective abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In cultures where there is a preference for male children, some women have sex selective abortions, which have partially replaced the earlier practice of female infanticide.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Some abortions are performed due to concerns over maternal health.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In 1990s, women cited maternal health as their main motivating factor in about a third of abortions in three of 27 countries analyzed.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In seven additional countries, about 7% of abortions were maternal health related.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In the U.S., the Supreme Court decisions in *Roe v.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Bolton*: "ruled that the state's interest in the life of the fetus became compelling only at the point of viability, defined as the point at which the fetus can survive independently of its mother.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Even after the point of viability, the state cannot favor the life of the fetus over the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Under the right of privacy, physicians must be free to use their "medical judgment for the preservation of the life or health of the mother".
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] On the same day that the Court decided Roe, it also decided Doe v.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Bolton, in which the Court defined health very broadly: "The medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The rate of cancer during pregnancy is 0.02–1%, and in many cases, cancer of the mother leads to consideration of abortion to protect the life of the mother, or in response to the potential damage that may occur to the fetus during treatment.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] This is particularly true for cervical cancer, the most common type of which occurs in 1 of every 2,000–13,000 pregnancies, for which initiation of treatment "cannot co-exist with preservation of fetal life (unless neoadjuvant chemotherapy is chosen)".
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Very early stage cervical cancers (I and IIa) may be treated by radical hysterectomy and pelvic lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or both, while later stages are treated by radiotherapy.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Chemotherapy may be used simultaneously.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Treatment of breast cancer during pregnancy also involves fetal considerations, because lumpectomy is discouraged in favor of modified radical mastectomy unless late-term pregnancy allows follow-up radiation therapy to be administered after the birth.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Exposure to a single chemotherapy drug is estimated to cause a 7.5–17% risk of teratogenic effects on the fetus, with higher risks for multiple drug treatments.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Treatment with more than 40 Gy of radiation usually causes spontaneous abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Exposure to much lower doses during the first trimester, especially 8 to 15 weeks of development, can cause intellectual disability or microcephaly, and exposure at this or subsequent stages can cause reduced intrauterine growth and birth weight.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Exposures above 0.005–0.025 Gy cause a dose-dependent reduction in IQ.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] It is possible to greatly reduce exposure to radiation with abdominal shielding, depending on how far the area to be irradiated is from the fetus.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The process of birth itself may also put the mother at risk.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Congenital disorders, revealed by prenatal screening, motivate some women to seek abortions.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Health outcomes of preterm births include a significant probability of long-term neurodevelopmental impairment before gestational age of 29 weeks, with a higher probability with decreasing gestational age.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In the United States, public opinion shifted after television personality Sherri Finkbine's was exposed to thalidomide, a teratogen, in her fifth month of pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Unable to obtain a legal abortion in the United States, Finkbine traveled to Sweden.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] From 1962 to 1965, an outbreak of German measles left 15,000 babies with severe birth defects.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In 1967, the American Medical Association publicly supported liberalization of abortion laws.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A National Opinion Research Center poll in 1965 showed 73% supported abortion when the mother's life was at risk, 57% when birth defects were present and 59% for pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Since ancient times, abortions have been done using a number of methods, including herbal medicines acting as abortifacients, sharp tools through the use of force, or through other traditional medicine methods.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Induced abortion has a long history and can be traced back to civilizations as varied as ancient China (abortifacient knowledge is often attributed to the mythological ruler Shennong), ancient India since its Vedic age, ancient Egypt with its Ebers Papyrus (c.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] 1550 BCE), and the Roman Empire in the time of Juvenal (c.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] One of the earliest known artistic representations of abortion is in a bas relief at Angkor Wat (c.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Found in a series of friezes that represent judgment after death in Hindu and Buddhist culture, it depicts the technique of abdominal abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In *Politics* (350 BCE), Aristotle condemned infanticide as a means of population control.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] He preferred abortion in such cases, with the restriction that it "must be practised on it before it has developed sensation and life; for the line between lawful and unlawful abortion will be marked by the fact of having sensation and being alive".
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Abortion has been a fairly common practice, and was not always illegal or controversial until the 19th century.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In Europe and North America, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century; the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Other medical practitioners in addition to some physicians advertised their services, and they were not widely regulated until the 19th century when the practice, sometimes called *restellism*, was banned in both the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Some 19th-century physicians, argued for anti-abortion laws on racist and misogynist as well as moral grounds.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Church groups were also highly influential in anti-abortion movements, and religious groups more so since the 20th century.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Some of the early anti-abortion laws punished only the doctor or abortionist, and while women could be criminally tried for a self-induced abortion, they were rarely prosecuted in general.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Some maintain that in the 19th century early abortions under the hygienic conditions in which midwives usually worked were relatively safe.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Several scholars argue that, despite improved medical procedures, the period from the 1930s until the 1970s saw more zealous enforcement of anti-abortion laws, alongside an increasing control of abortion providers by organized crime.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In 1920, Soviet Russia became the first country to legalize abortion after Lenin insisted that no woman be forced to give birth.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Abortion was then legalized in some form in Iceland (1935), Sweden (1938), Nazi Germany (1935) and Japan (1948) Beginning in the second half of the 20th century, abortion was legalized in a greater number of countries.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In the Catholic Church, opinion was divided on how serious abortion was in comparison with such acts as contraception and oral or anal sex.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The Catholic Church did not begin vigorously opposing abortion until the 19th century.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] As early as ~100 CE, the *Didache* taught that abortion was sinful.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Several historians argue that prior to the 19th century most Catholic authors did not regard termination of pregnancy before quickening or ensoulment as an abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] 1585–1590) was the first Pope to institute a Church policy labeling all abortion as homicide and condemning abortion regardless of the stage of pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Sixtus V's pronouncement was reversed in 1591 by Pope Gregory XIV.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In the recodification of 1917 Code of Canon Law, *Apostolicae Sedis* was strengthened, in part to remove a possible reading that excluded excommunication of the mother.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Statements made in the *Catechism of the Catholic Church*, the codified summary of the Church's teachings, considers abortion from the moment of conception as homicide and called for the end of legal abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Denominations that support abortion rights with some limits include the United Methodist Church, Episcopal Church, Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and Presbyterian Church USA.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A 2014 Guttmacher survey of abortion patients in the United States found that many reported a religious affiliation: 24% were Catholic while 30% were Protestant.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A 1995 survey reported that Catholic women are as likely as the general population to terminate a pregnancy, Protestants are less likely to do so, and evangelical Christians are the least likely to do so.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that most Christian denominations were against overturning *Roe v.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Wade,* which in the United States legalized abortion, at around 70%, except White Evangelicals at 35%.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In Judaism, the fetus is not considered to have a human soul until it is safely outside of the woman, is viable, and has taken its first breath.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] The fetus is considered valuable property of the woman and not a human life while in the womb (Exodus 21:22-23).
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] While Judaism encourages people to be fruitful and multiply by having children, abortion is allowed and is deemed necessary when a pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Several religions, including Judaism, which disagree that human life begins at conception, support the legality of abortion on religious freedom grounds.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] In Islam, abortion is traditionally permitted until a point in time when Muslims believe the soul enters the fetus, considered by various theologians to be at conception, 40 days after conception, 120 days after conception, or at quickening.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Abortion is largely heavily restricted or forbidden in areas of high Islamic faith such as the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Hindu views on abortion are diverse and lack a single authoritative position, shaped by principles like ahimsa (non-violence), karma, and reincarnation, which typically regard it as morally wrong for interrupting the soul's cycle.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Scriptures often equate abortion to grave sins, with the fetus considered ensouled from conception or early gestation.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] However, it may be ethically permissible to save the mother's life or in cases of severe fetal abnormalities, prioritizing lesser harm.
[src:abortion/abortion-p01] Modern opinions differ regionally: In India, a majority view abortion as generally illegal, while in the US, most Hindus support legal access in all or most cases.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Induced abortion has long been the source of considerable debate.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Ethical, moral, philosophical, biological, religious and legal issues surrounding abortion are related to value systems.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Opinions of abortion may be about fetal rights, governmental authority, and women's rights.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] In both public and private debate, arguments presented in favor of or against abortion access focus on either the moral permissibility of an induced abortion, or the justification of laws permitting or restricting abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] The World Medical Association Declaration on Therapeutic Abortion notes, "circumstances bringing the interests of a mother into conflict with the interests of her unborn child create a dilemma and raise the question as to whether or not the pregnancy should be deliberately terminated".
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Abortion debates, especially pertaining to abortion laws, are often spearheaded by groups advocating one of these two positions.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Groups who favor greater legal restrictions on abortion, including complete prohibition, most often describe themselves as "pro-life" while groups who are against such legal restrictions describe themselves as "pro-choice".
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] The median voters stance on abortion varies by jurisdiction and can result in swing votes.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Current laws pertaining to abortion are diverse.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Religious, moral, and cultural factors continue to influence abortion laws throughout the world.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] The right to life, the right to liberty, the right to security of person, and the right to reproductive health are major issues of human rights that sometimes constitute the basis for the existence or absence of abortion laws.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] In jurisdictions where abortion is legal, certain requirements must often be met before a woman may obtain a legal abortion (an abortion performed without the woman's consent is considered feticide and is generally illegal).
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] These requirements usually depend on the age of the fetus, often using a trimester-based system to regulate the window of legality, or as in the U.S., on a doctor's evaluation of the fetus' viability.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Some jurisdictions require a waiting period before the procedure, prescribe the distribution of information on fetal development, or require that parents be contacted if their minor daughter requests an abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Many restrictions are waived in emergency situations.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] China, which has ended their one-child policy, and now has a three-child policy, has at times incorporated mandatory abortions as part of their population control strategy.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Other jurisdictions ban abortion almost entirely.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Many, but not all, of these allow legal abortions in a variety of circumstances.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] These circumstances vary based on jurisdiction, but may include whether the pregnancy is a result of rape or incest, the fetus' development is impaired, the woman's physical or mental well-being is endangered, or socioeconomic considerations make childbirth a hardship.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] In countries where abortion is banned entirely, such as Nicaragua, medical authorities have recorded rises in maternal death directly and indirectly due to pregnancy as well as deaths due to doctors' fears of prosecution if they treat other gynecological emergencies.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Some countries, such as Bangladesh, that nominally ban abortion, may also support clinics that perform abortions under the guise of menstrual hygiene.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] This is also a terminology in traditional medicine.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] In places where abortion is illegal or carries heavy social stigma, pregnant women may engage in medical tourism and travel to countries where they can terminate their pregnancies.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Women on Waves has provided medication abortion and education on a ship in international waters off the coast of countries with restrictive abortion laws.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Women without the means to travel can resort to providers of illegal abortions or attempt to perform an abortion by themselves.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Sonography and amniocentesis allow parents to determine sex before childbirth.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] The development of this technology has led to sex-selective abortion, or the termination of a fetus based on its sex.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] The selective termination of a female fetus is most common.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Sex-selective abortion is partially responsible for the noticeable disparities between the birth rates of male and female children in some countries.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] The preference for male children is reported in many areas of Asia, and abortion used to limit female births has been reported in Taiwan, South Korea, India, and China.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] This deviation from the standard birth rates of males and females occurs despite the fact that the country in question may have officially banned sex-selective abortion or even sex-screening.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Many countries have taken legislative steps to reduce the incidence of sex-selective abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] At the International Conference on Population and Development in 1994 over 180 states agreed to eliminate "all forms of discrimination against the girl child and the root causes of son preference", conditions also condemned by a PACE resolution in 2011.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] On the other hand, measures to reduce gender inequality can reduce the prevalence of such abortions without attendant negative consequences.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Abortion providers and facilities have been subjected to violence, including murder, assault, arson, and bombing.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Some scholars consider anti-abortion violence to be within the definition of terrorism, a view shared by some governments.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] In the U.S. and Canada, over 8,000 incidents of violence, trespassing, and death threats have been recorded by providers since 1977, including over 200 bombings/arsons and hundreds of assaults.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Abortion clinics have also been targeted by acid attacks, invasions, and vandalism The majority of abortion opponents have not been involved in violent acts.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Physicians and other abortion clinic staff have been murdered by abortion opponents.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] In the United States, at least four physicians have been murdered in connection with their work at abortion clinics, including David Gunn (1993), John Britton (1994), Barnett Slepian (1998), and George Tiller (2009).
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] In Canada, gynecologist Garson Romalis survived murder attempts in both 1994 and 2000.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Besides physicians, killings have targeted other clinic staff, such as John Salvi's 1994 murder of two receptionists in Massachusetts clinic and Peter Knight's 2001 murder of a security guard in a Melbourne clinic.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Notable perpetrators of anti-abortion violence include Eric Rudolph, Scott Roeder, Shelley Shannon, and Paul Hill, the first person to be executed in the United States for murdering an abortion provider.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Some countries have laws to protecting access to abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Such laws prevent abortion opponents from interfering with access to legal abortion services.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] For example, the American Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act bars the use of threats or violence to interfere with abortion access.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Abortion access laws may also establish safe access zones around abortion clinics, with limits on protests and enhanced penalties for anti-abortion violence.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Psychological pressure may also be used to limit abortion access.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Some protestors record women entering clinics on camera.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Spontaneous abortion occurs in various animals.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] For example, in sheep it may be caused by stress or physical exertion, such as crowding through doors or being chased by dogs.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] In cows, abortion may be caused by contagious disease, such as brucellosis or *Campylobacter*, but can often be controlled by vaccination.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Eating pine needles can also induce abortions in cows.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Several plants, including broomweed, skunk cabbage, poison hemlock, and tree tobacco, are known to cause fetal deformities and abortion in cattle, and in sheep and goats.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] In horses, a fetus may be aborted or resorbed if it has lethal white syndrome.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Foal embryos that are homozygous for the dominant white gene (WW) are theorized to also be aborted or resorbed before birth.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] In many species of sharks and rays, stress-induced abortions occur frequently upon capture.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Viral infection can cause abortion in dogs.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Cats can experience spontaneous abortion for many reasons, including hormonal imbalance.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] A combined abortion and spaying are performed on pregnant cats, especially in trap–neuter–return programs, to prevent unwanted kittens from being born.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Female rodents may terminate a pregnancy when exposed to the smell of a male not responsible for the pregnancy, known as the Bruce effect.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Abortion may also be induced in animals, in the context of animal husbandry.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] For example, abortion may be induced in mares that have been mated improperly, or that have been purchased by owners who did not realize the mares were pregnant, or that are pregnant with twin foals.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Feticide can occur in horses and zebras due to male harassment of pregnant mares or forced copulation, although the frequency in the wild has been questioned.
[src:abortion/abortion-p02] Male gray langur monkeys may attack females following male takeover, causing miscarriage.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The issue of induced abortion remains divisive in public life, with recurring arguments to liberalize or restrict access to legal abortion services.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Some abortion-rights supporters are divided as to the types of abortion services that should be available under different circumstances, including periods in the pregnancy such as late term abortions, in which access may or may not be restricted.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Many of the terms used in the debate are political framing terms used to validate one's stance while invalidating the opposition.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] For example, the labels pro-choice and pro-life imply endorsement of widely held values such as liberty and freedom, while suggesting that the opposition must be "anti-choice" or "anti-life".
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] These views do not always align along a strict binary.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In one poll conducted by the Public Religion Research Institute, the ambiguity of the terms led 70% of Americans to identify as 'pro-choice,' while nearly two-thirds simultaneously identified as "pro-life".
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] It was found that, in polling, respondents would label themselves differently when given specific details about the circumstances around an abortion including factors such as rape, incest, viability of the fetus, and survivability of the mother.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The Associated Press favors the terms "abortion rights" and "anti-abortion" instead.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion practices date back to 1550 BCE, based on the findings of practices recorded on documents.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion has been an active practice since Egyptian medicine.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Centuries later, abortion was a topic taken up by feminism.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Mohr, there was an earlier acceptance of abortion, and opposition to abortion, including anti-abortion laws, only came into being in the 19th century.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] It was not always a crime and was generally not illegal until quickening, which occurred between the fourth and sixth months of pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In the 19th century, the medical profession was generally opposed to abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Mohr argues that the opposition arose due to competition between men with medical degrees and women without one, such as Madame Drunette.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The practice of abortion was one of the first medical specialities, and was practiced by unlicensed people; well-off people had abortions and paid well.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The press played a key role in rallying support for anti-abortion laws.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The ideas of the legalization of abortion in the late 19th century were often opposed by feminists, seeing it as a means of relieving men of responsibility.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In *The Revolution*, which was an official published newspaper of women's rights that went out weekly, operated by Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Anthony, an anonymous contributor signing "A" wrote in 1869 about the subject, arguing that instead of merely attempting to pass a law against abortion, the root cause must also be addressed.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] *The Revolution* newspaper highly impacted the women's rights movement, and for the first time, it seemed like women's voices were being heard through the proclamations of these unacknowledged subjects regarding women and their everyday rights and safety as citizens.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The writer wrote that simply passing an anti-abortion law would "be only mowing off the top of the noxious weed, while the root remains. ...
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] No matter what the motive, love of ease, or a desire to save from suffering the unborn innocent, the woman is awfully guilty who commits the deed.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Between 1900 and 1965, there were not any anti-abortion movements or rallies because states had already passed a law banning abortions at all levels, including prescriptions and procedures.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The only exception for a woman to get an abortion without fear of legal retribution was if a licensed physician determined the abortion would protect the mother's life.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Physicians who provide abortions and women who have abortions were constantly harassed by courts and prosecutors.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In the 1960s, some states began to request changes with the abortion law.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In 1959, a group of experts set up a model enactment that supported the advancement of the abortion laws.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] These experts suggested that the abortion laws should provide exemptions for women that were sexually assaulted or for a baby that may not have a good quality of life.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The abortion-rights movement became a controversial topic in the United States regarding abortion and reproduction.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The movement towards the liberalization of abortion law emerged in the 1920s and 1930s in the context of the victories that had been recently won in the area of birth control.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Campaigners including Marie Stopes in England and Margaret Sanger in the US had succeeded in bringing the issue into the open, and birth control clinics were established that offered family planning advice and contraceptive methods to women in need.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Birth control is a method of pregnancy prevention through controlled contraception.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In 1929, the Infant Life Preservation Act was passed in the United Kingdom, which amended the law (Offences against the Person Act 1861) so that an abortion carried out in good faith, for the sole purpose of preserving the life of the mother, would not be an offense.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Many citizens had mixed opinions on this, but ultimately started protesting this as child destruction.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Child destruction was known as taking the life of a viable unborn child during a pregnancy or at birth, before it is independent of its mother.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] If there is an intent of death and no good faith is carried out in the process in order to protect the mother's livelihood, the offense carries a maximum punishment of life imprisonment.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The Infant Life Preservation Act defines the difference between murder and abortion-the causing of a miscarriage.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Stella Browne was a leading birth control campaigner, who increasingly began to venture into the more contentious issue of abortion in the 1930s.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Browne's beliefs were heavily influenced by the work of Havelock Ellis, Edward Carpenter and other sexologists.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] She came to strongly believe that working women should have the choice to become pregnant and to terminate their pregnancy while they worked in the horrible circumstances surrounding a pregnant woman who was still required to do hard labor during her pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In this case she argued that doctors should give free information about birth control to women that wanted to know about it.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] This would give women agency over their own circumstances and allow them to decide whether they wanted to be mothers or not.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] These talks urged women to take matters of their sexuality and their health into their own hands.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] She became increasingly interested in her view of the woman's right to terminate their pregnancies, and in 1929, she brought forward her lecture "The Right to Abortion" in front of the World Sexual Reform Congress in London.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In 1931, Browne began to develop her argument for women's right to decide to have an abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] She again began touring, giving lectures on abortion and the negative consequences that followed if women were unable to terminate pregnancies of their own choosing such as: suicide, injury, permanent invalidism, madness and blood-poisoning.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] On February 17, 1936, Janet Chance, Alice Jenkins and Joan Malleson established the Abortion Law Reform Association as the first advocacy organization for abortion liberalization.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The association promoted access to abortion in the United Kingdom and campaigned for the elimination of legal obstacles.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In its first year ALRA recruited 35 members, and by 1939 had almost 400 members.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The ALRA was very active between 1936 and 1939 sending speakers around the country to talk about Labour and Equal Citizenship and attempted, though most often unsuccessfully, to have letters and articles published in newspapers.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] They became the most popular when a member of the ALRA's Medico-Legal Committee received the case of a fourteen-year-old girl who had been raped, and received a termination of this pregnancy from Dr.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Joan Malleson, a progenitor of the ALRA.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In 1938, Joan Malleson precipitated one of the most influential cases in British abortion law when she referred a pregnant fourteen-year old rape survivor to gynaecologist Aleck Bourne.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] He performed an abortion, then illegal, and was put on trial on charges of procuring abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Bourne was eventually acquitted in *R v.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Bourne*as his actions were "...an example of disinterested conduct in consonance with the highest traditions of the profession".
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] This court case set a precedent that doctors could not be prosecuted for performing an abortion in cases where pregnancy would probably cause "mental and physical wreck".
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The Abortion Law Reform Association continued its campaigning after the Second World War, and this, combined with broad social changes brought the issue of abortion back into the political arena in the 1960s.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In America an abortion reform movement emerged in the 1960s.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In 1964, Gerri Santoro of Connecticut died trying to obtain an illegal abortion and her photo became the symbol of the abortion rights movement.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Some women's rights activist groups developed their own skills to provide abortions to women who could not obtain them elsewhere.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] As an example, in Chicago, a group known as "Jane" operated a floating abortion clinic throughout much of the 1960s.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Women seeking the procedure would call a designated number and be given instructions on how to find "Jane".
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In the late 1960s, a number of organizations were formed to mobilize opinion both against and for the legalization of abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The forerunner of the NARAL Pro-Choice America was formed in 1969 to oppose restrictions on abortion and expand access to abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In late 1973, NARAL became the National Abortion Rights Action League.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The landmark judicial ruling of the Supreme Court in *Roe v.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Wade* ruled that a Texas statute forbidding abortion except when necessary to save the life of the mother was unconstitutional.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] This was back in 1970, where Jane Roe, (which was actually a fictional name used in the court documents in order to protect the plaintiff's identity), had filed a lawsuit against Henry Wade.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] He was the district attorney of Dallas County in Texas, where Jane Roe resided.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] She was challenging a Texas law making abortion illegal except by a doctor's orders to save a woman's life.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The Court arrived at its decision by concluding that the issue of abortion and abortion rights falls under the right to privacy.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The Court held that a right to privacy existed and included the right to have an abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The court found that a mother had a right to abortion until viability, a point to be determined by the abortion doctor.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] After viability a woman can obtain an abortion for health reasons, which the Court defined broadly to include psychological well-being in the decision *Doe v.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] From the 1970s, and the spread of second-wave feminism, abortion and reproductive rights became unifying issues among various women's rights groups in Canada, the United States, the Netherlands, Britain, Norway, France, Germany, and Italy.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In 2015, in the wake of the House of Representatives' vote to defund Planned Parenthood, Lindy West, Amelia Bonow and Kimberly Morrison launched ShoutYourAbortion to "remind supporters and critics alike abortion is a legal right to anyone who wants or needs it".
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In 2019, the You Know Me movement started as a response to the successful 2019 passage of fetal heartbeat bills in five states in the United States, most notably the passing of anti-abortion laws in Georgia (House Bill 381), Ohio (House Bill 68) and Alabama (House Bill 314).
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] This movement was started off by actress Busy Philipps because she had previously had an abortion when she was a teen.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The actress and many others believe that it is important for women to speak up and shift the narrative, especially because abortion is such a taboo subject.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In the mid-19th century, concerns around abortion only consisted of the danger of a woman being poisoned and risking her health, not because of religion, ethics, or diplomacy.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Ending a pregnancy before the fetus began movement, or "post-quickening" was only a wrongdoing, not a crime.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The laws that were against abortions post-quickening removals were put in place to protect the well-being of the women that were pregnant, not the fetal life.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] It was more common for women to die during early terminations due to the usage of pre-owned instruments as opposed to natural abortifacients.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Some women who engaged in quickening abortions were not prosecuted because there was no evidence and quickening was hard to prove.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Between 1900 and 1965, there were not any anti-abortion movements or rallies because states had already passed a law banning abortions at all levels included the prescription of drugs or undergoing procedures.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The only exception for a woman to proceed with an abortion without worrying about breaking any anti-abortion laws is if a licensed physician were to prove that the abortion was for the protection of the mother's life.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion care providers and women who had obtained an abortion were pestered by courts and prosecutors.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In the 1960s, some states began to request changes, around the abortion law, from their states.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In 1959, a group of experts set up a model enactment that supported the advancement of the fetus removal laws that were put in place.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] These experts suggested that the abortion laws should exempt women that were sexually assaulted, whose babies well-being were to be questioned and whose babies that were to be born out of its true, natural or original state.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The Abortion Rights Movement became a cultural shift in The United States about the intentions of reproduction and abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Wade* verdict changed the abortion laws altogether, making abortion legal.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Many physicians and healthcare professionals jeopardized their medical licenses, risked being put in prison and fined by the state because they wanted to continue to provide abortions.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] There were more than 1,000 abortion laws passed and enacted between 2011 and 2019 that limited access to abortion procedures.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Some of these laws forbid a woman getting an abortion past a certain gestational age and was also based on race and specific pregnancy conditions.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Other laws were established that ban particular abortion methods.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Targeted regulation of abortion providers (TRAP) was put in place to target abortion clinics by demanding unnecessary requirements that made it hard for women to get an abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Opponents of abortion rights claim that these requirements are for the safety of the mother and child, but that has not been scientifically proven.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] TRAP has placed limitations on abortion facilities to make it more difficult for them to provide abortion services that will essentially force them to not provide abortion services at all.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] TRAP policies have been put in place by 26 states as of 2020.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] During the pandemic, numerous states prohibited non-essential medical procedures, including abortion services.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Policymakers in twelve states saw this as a chance to certify abortion as non-essential, therefore ending services.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Jackson Women's Health Organization overturned Roe v.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Wade, removing the federal constitutional right to abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] This left abortion laws and restrictions up to each individual state.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] South Africa allows abortion on demand under its Choice on Termination of Pregnancy Act.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Most African nations, however, have abortion bans except in cases where the woman's life or health is at risk.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] A number of abortion-rights international organizations have made altering abortion laws and expanding family planning services in sub-Saharan Africa and the developing world a top priority.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] But there are only five countries in Africa where abortion is legal and those countries are Cape Verde, South Africa, Tunisia, Mozambique and Saõ Tome & Principe.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] 8.2 million abortions were performed each year in Africa.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] This number increased drastically compared to the 4.6 million abortions that were performed during 1990–1994.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] But this increased number of abortions is due to the increase of women that are reproducing at a young age.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Approximately 93% of women within their reproductive age live in countries that have very restrictive abortion laws and abortion is only legal in 10 out of 54 African countries, leading to fewer women not being able to obtain a safe procedure.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The World Health Organization only recommends trained personnel when performing induced abortions but not many women in Africa have access to trained professionals who are able to provide them with the best service to decrease the number of complications due to abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Approximately 1.6 million women are treated for abortion-related complications and only one in four abortions in Africa are safe.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Africa has the highest number of deaths that are related to abortion and this is due to the most common complication of abortion that consist of excessive blood loss and an incomplete abortion that can lead to an infection.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] During 2010–2014, 36 million abortions were performed in Asia.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Majority of abortions occurred in Central and South Asia at a rate of 16 million in India and Asia and 13 million in China alone.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Although the abortions performed in Asia are not known, there is an estimated 4.6 million women who are treated because they have complications due to the performance of an unsafe abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The major complication of abortion is an incomplete abortion where a woman can experience an immoderate amount of blood loss and can develop an infection.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Less common complications of abortion include a woman going into septic shock, damaging the internal organs and causing the peritoneum to be inflamed, all due to the unclean and unsterilized instruments that are being used doing the procedure.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Untreated complications from abortions can leave women to experience negative health consequences for life that include infertility, chronic pain, inflammation of the reproductive organs and pelvic inflammatory disease.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Unsafe abortions go deeper than just a woman's health but they lead to reduced productivity for women increased costs to an already struggling family.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Although it is not completely known, a drug known as misoprostol is used to perform abortions in Asian countries and evidence shows that the sales of this drug has increased in Asia over the course of years.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] On record, out of all the pregnancies in Asia, 27 percent of them end in abortions.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] This is the reason for the Asia Safe Abortion Partnership (ASAP).
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] This program was formed to increase the accessibility to safe and legal abortions and health care that is needed after any abortion service.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] 50 countries occupy Asia and out of those 50, 17 countries do not have a restriction on abortions excluding, gestational limits and permission from a spouse or parent.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] ASAP satisfies the demand for safe and accessible abortions through educational and advocacy.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] By grouping with other countries to promote advocacy networks, ASAP has created a worldwide and generational feminist power that advocates for women's abortion rights, autonomy and dignity.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Anti-abortion groups have tried their best to discriminate the reproductive autonomy of women but ASAP has members spread across 20 countries that promote the women's movement for abortion rights, laws, and access.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Even though abortion is legal in Asia, that does not mean that women always have access or adequate health care during these times.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] For example, abortions in India have been legal since 1951 but women who are particularly poor or marginalized make up 50% of unsafe abortions.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Women in the Philippines are more than likely to undergo an unsafe and unsanitary abortion causing around 1,000 death annually due to abortion complications.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The Philippines along with Iraq and Laos are the countries that has not made abortion legal, excluding legal exceptions, therefore they have not made it available to where women can have admissions to legal abortions that are safe for them and their bodies.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Countries such as Afghanistan, Thailand, China and Lebanon, have all been impacted by the determined long-term feminist motion by ASAP for women's abortion rights.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] This work ranges from workshops, journalists, advocates to menstrual management, violence against women, and issues surrounded unplanned pregnancies.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] "Youth champions" were created by ASAP to share the knowledge that they have learned to their peers about sexual activity, abortions, women's rights and reproductions, reproductive health, and the abortion rights movement in general.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Chapter XXIX of the Penal Code of Japan makes abortion illegal in Japan.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Other people, including the mother herself, trying to abort the fetus can be punished by the law.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] People trying to practice abortion without the consent of the woman can also be punished, including the doctors.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion has been illegal in South Korea since 1953 but on April 11, 2019, South Korea's Constitutional Court ruled the abortion ban unconstitutional and called for the law to be amended.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The Constitutional Court has taken into consideration abortion-rights cases by women because they find the abortion ban as unconstitutional.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] To help support the legalization of abortion in South Korea, thousands of advocates compiled a petition for the Blue House to consider lifting the ban.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Due to the abortion ban, this has led to many dangerous self-induced abortions and other illegal practices of abortion that needs more attention.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] This is why there are advocates challenging the law to put into perspective the negative factors this abortion ban brings.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] By making abortion illegal in South Korea, this also creates an issue when it comes to women's rights and their own rights to their bodies.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] As a result, many women's advocate groups were created and acted together to protest against the abortion ban law.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Global Day of Action is a form of protest that advocates to make a change and bring more awareness to global warming.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] During this protest, a group of feminist Korean advocates called, "The Joint Action for Reproductive Justice" connected with one another to promote concerns that requires more attention and needs a quick change such as making abortion legal.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] By combining different advocate groups that serves different purposes and their own goals they want to achieve into one event, it helps promote all the different aspects of reality that needs to change.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In 1920, under the leadership of Vladimir Lenin, Russia became the first country in the world to legally permit abortion, no matter the circumstances.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] But in the 20th century, the laws surrounding abortion were repeatedly modified between the years of 1936 and 1955.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] According to data from the United Nations in 2010, Russia had the highest rates of abortion per woman of reproduction.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Results from the abortion rates of China and Russia were compared and out of a population of 1.3 billion people, China only reported 13 million abortions, a huge difference when contrasted to the population in Russia of 143 million people with 1.2 million abortions.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Since abortion was illegal in the Russian Empire, it was not recognized in the Domostroi.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The Domostroi was a set of tasks that were to be followed that were structured around rules, instructions surrounded by religious, social and domestic issues that were centered within the Russian Society.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] These rules enforced respect and compliance to God and the church.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Different rulers had different views about abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] During Romanov's reign, abortion was illegal, frowned up, and if a woman were to go through with an abortion, her punishment was death.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] But after Romanov's reign ended, Peter the Great lifted the punishment of death for abortions but it was still considered a serious issue in 1917.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Before the punishment for abortions was death, according to the Russian Penal Code that dates back to 1462–1463, women were dispossessed of their basic human and civil rights and banned from the city or they were forced into hard labor.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] These harsh treatments and illegality surrounded around abortion still did not stop women from pursuing abortions.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] "Black Market" abortions were known as unauthorized and discreet procedures done by women who have experience in childbirth.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] These women were known as older women that were midwives and rural midwives, respectfully.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Although these women were not abortion care providers, they were the only accessible obstetric personnel that women could go to without facing the harsh punishment and consequences forced upon by the Russian Society.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Since adequate medical care was not provided for women looking to terminate their pregnancy, midwives and nurses from villages were trained to care for these women the best to their ability, but of course with illegal abortions there are always repercussions.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] During the Soviet period in Russia, abortions ranked as the highest rates world-wide.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] After the Soviet period ended inn the Russian union, abortion numbers decreased with further enforced sex education courses and use of contraceptive birth control.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion was illegal in the Republic of Ireland except when the woman's life was threatened by a medical condition (including risk of suicide), since a 1983 referendum (aka 8th Amendment) amended the constitution.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Subsequent amendments in 1992 (after the X Case) – the thirteenth and fourteenth – guaranteed the right to travel abroad (for abortions) and to distribute and obtain information of "lawful services" available in other countries.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Two proposals to remove suicide risk as a ground for abortion were rejected by the people, in a referendum in 1992 and in 2002.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Thousands of women get around the ban by privately traveling to the other European countries (typically Britain and the Netherlands) to undergo termination, or by ordering abortion pills from Women on Web online and taking them in Ireland.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Sinn Féin, the Labour Party, Social Democrats, Green Party, Communist Party, Socialist Party and Irish Republican Socialist Party have made their official policies to support abortion rights.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Mainstream center-right parties such as Fianna Fáil and Fine Gael do not have official policies on abortion rights but allow their members to take a conscience vote in support of abortion in limited circumstances.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Aontú, founded in January 2019, is firmly anti-abortionist and seeks to "protect the right to life".
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] After the death of Savita Halappanavar in 2012, there has been a renewed campaign to repeal the eighth amendment and legalize abortion.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] As of January 2017, the Irish government has set up a citizens assembly to look at the issue.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Their proposals, broadly supported by a cross-party Oireachtas committee, include repeal of the 8th Amendment, unrestricted access to abortion for the first 12 weeks of pregnancy and no-term limits for special cases of fatal foetal abnormalities, rape and incest.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] A referendum on the repealing of the 8th Amendment was held on May 25, 2018.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Together for Yes, a cross-society group formed from the Coalition to Repeal the 8th Amendment, the National Women's Council of Ireland and the Abortion Rights Campaign, were the official campaign group for repeal in the referendum.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Activists utilized social media to bring the narrative of women's voices to the forefront of the campaign, making clear that the Eighth Amendment was dangerous for pregnant women to try and encourage voters to vote in favor of repeal.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The 67% majority in favor of repeal is a testament to these stories and the women who braved the public Twitter sphere to change the law around women's reproductive lives.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Despite being part of the United Kingdom, abortion remained illegal in Northern Ireland, except in cases when the woman is threatened by a medical condition, physical or mental, until 2019.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Women seeking abortions had to travel to England.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In October 2019, abortion up to 12 weeks was legalized, to begin in April 2020, but remains near-unobtainable.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Poland initially held abortion to be legal in 1958 by the communist government, but was later banned after restoration of democracy in 1989.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Currently, abortion is illegal in all cases except for rape or when the fetus or mother is in fatal conditions.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The wide spread of Catholic Church in Poland within the country has made abortion socially 'unacceptable'.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The Pope has had major influence on the acceptance of abortion within Poland.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Several landmark court cases have had substantial influence on the current status of abortion, including *Tysiac v Poland*.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In the United Kingdom, the Abortion Act 1967 legalized abortion on a wide number of grounds, except in Northern Ireland.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] 4. shows there is evidence of extreme fetal abnormality i.e. the child would be seriously physically or mentally handicapped after birth and during life.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] However, the criterion of risk to mental and physical health is applied broadly, and *de facto* makes abortion available on demand, though this still requires the consent of two National Health Service doctors.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Abortions in Great Britain are provided at no out-of-pocket cost to the patient by the NHS.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The Labour Party and the Liberal Democrats are predominantly pro-abortion-rights parties, though with significant minorities in each either holding more restrictive definitions of the right to choose, or subscribing to an anti-abortion analysis.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The Conservative Party is more evenly split between both camps and its former leader, David Cameron, supports abortion on demand in the early stages of pregnancy.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion laws in the Middle East reflect variation of opinions.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Some countries permit abortion in cases involving a pregnant woman's well-being, fetal impairment, and rape.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion was widely practiced during the colonial period, and allowed a longer term termination.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] By the 19th century, progressive interpretations cut the abortion time limit down to the first trimester.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] However, a 2008 World Health Organization report estimated 900,000 unsafe abortion occurred each year in the Middle Eastern and Northern Africa regions.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] While many countries have decriminalized abortions and made it more accessible, there are still a few remaining countries yet to do so.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] In April 2005, the Iranian Parliament approved a new bill easing the conditions by also allowing abortion in certain cases when the fetus shows signs of handicap.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Legal abortion is now allowed if the mother's life is in danger, and also in cases of fetal abnormalities that makes it not viable after birth (such as anencephaly) or produce difficulties for mother to take care of it after birth, such as major thalassemia or bilateral polycystic kidney disease.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion-rights advocacy in the United States is centered in the United States abortion-rights movement.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Across the world, there are only four countries in which abortion is completely banned.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Honduras, Dominican Republic, Nicaragua, and El Salvador have yet to legalize abortions, even if it is for the woman's health and safety.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Since 2018, there have been no changes in the laws regarding abortion in these Latin-America countries.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The Ministry of Public Health collected data that showed nearly half the pregnancies in the Dominican Republic alone are unwanted or unplanned; often stemming from incest or rape.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Women in South America continue fighting for their rights and protection, but there has been no recent call of action.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Because Argentina has been very restrictive against abortion, reliable reporting on abortion rates is unavailable.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Argentina has long been a strongly Catholic country, and protesters seeking legalized abortion in 2013 directed anger toward the Catholic Church.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] On December 11, 2020, after a 20-hour debate, the Chamber of Deputies voted 131 to 117 (6 abstentions) to approve a bill legalizing abortion up to 14 weeks after conception.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The bill's passing resulted in large-scale celebrations by abortion rights activists who had long campaigned for it.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] The Argentine Senate approved the bill 38–29 on December 29, and it is expected to be signed by President Alberto Fernandez.
[src:abortion/abortion-rights-movements] Argentina will become the fourth Latin American country to legalize abortion.
